{"title_page": "Leptospermum maxwellii", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|image = \n|status = \n|status_system = \n|genus = Leptospermum\n|species = maxwellii\n|authority = [[Spencer Le Marchant Moore|S.Moore]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Leptospermum maxwellii'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/99140|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n\n'''''Leptospermum maxwellii''''' is a species of often low-growing shrub that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Western Australia. It has thin, flaking bark, egg-shaped leaves, white flowers arranged singly on short side shoots and fruit with the remains of the [[sepal]]s attached.\n\n==Description==\n''Leptospermum maxwellii'' is a shrub that typically grows to a height of {{cvt|0.5-2.3|m}} and has thin, flaking bark. The leaves are egg-shaped, narrower towards the base, up to {{cvt|12|mm}} long and {{cvt|1-5|mm}} wide on a short [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]]. The flowers are white and are usually borne in pairs on short side shoots. There are reddish brown [[bract]]s and [[Bract#Bracteole|bracteoles]] at the base of the buds but that are shed early in the flower's development. The [[Hypanthium|floral cup]] is {{cvt|2-3|mm}} long and marked with vertical ridges.  The sepals are {{cvt|1-2|mm}} long and triangular and the [[petal]]s {{cvt|2.5-5|mm}} long. Flowering mainly occurs from September to November and the fruit is up to {{cvt|5|mm}} in diameter and wrinkled with the remnants of the sepals attached.<ref name=\"Telopea\">{{cite journal |last1=Thompson |first1=Joy |title=A revision of the genus ''Leptospermum'' (Myrtaceae) |journal=Telopea |date=1989 |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=351\u2013352}}</ref><ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Leptospermum maxwellii''|id=5851}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\n''Leptospermum maxwellii'' was first formally described in 1920 by [[Spencer Le Marchant Moore]] and the description was published in the ''[[Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society|Journal of the Linnean Society, Botany]]'' from specimens collected by [[George Maxwell]] near the [[Fitzgerald River]].<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Leptospermum maxwellii''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/525564|publisher=APNI|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"S.Moore\">{{cite journal |last1=Moore |first1=Spencer Le M. |title=A Contribution to the Flora of Australia |journal=The Journal of the Linnean Society, Botany |date=1920 |volume=45 |page=201 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/8410#page/215/mode/1up |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''maxwellii'') honours the collector of the [[Type (biology)|type]] specimens.<ref name=\"Sharr\">{{cite book |author=[[Francis Aubie Sharr]]|title=Western Australian Plant Names and their Meanings |date=2019 |publisher=Four Gables Press |location=Kardinya, Western Australia |isbn=9780958034180 |page=249}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThis tea tree grows on stony ridges in sandy soils over granite or laterite, in the [[Esperance Plains]] and [[Mallee (biogeographic region)|Mallee]] [[IBRA|biogeographic regions]].<ref name=\"Telopea\" /><ref name=\"FloraBase\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15368843}}\n\n[[Category:Leptospermum|maxwellii]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1920]]\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|image = \n|status = \n|status_system = \n|genus = Leptospermum\n|species = maxwellii\n|authority = [[Spencer Le Marchant Moore|S.Moore]]<ref name=\"APC\">{{cite web |title=''Leptospermum maxwellii'' |url=https://biodiversity.org.au/nsl/services/apc-format/display/99140|website=Australian Plant Census |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> \n}}\n\n'''''Leptospermum maxwellii''''' is a species of often low-growing shrub that is [[Endemism|endemic]] to Western Australia. It has thin, flaking bark, egg-shaped leaves, white flowers arranged singly on short side shoots and fruit with the remains of the [[sepal]]s attached.\n\n==Description==\n''Leptospermum maxwellii'' is a shrub that typically grows to a height of {{cvt|0.5-2.3|m}} and has thin, flaking bark. The leaves are egg-shaped, narrower towards the base, up to {{cvt|12|mm}} long and {{cvt|1-5|mm}} wide on a short [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]]. The flowers are white and are usually borne in pairs on short side shoots. There are reddish brown [[bract]]s and [[Bract#Bracteole|bracteoles]] at the base of the buds but that are shed early in the flower's development. The [[Hypanthium|floral cup]] is {{cvt|2-3|mm}} long and marked with vertical ridges.  The sepals are {{cvt|1-2|mm}} long and triangular and the [[petal]]s {{cvt|2.5-5|mm}} long. Flowering mainly occurs from September to November and the fruit is up to {{cvt|5|mm}} in diameter and wrinkled with the remnants of the sepals attache.<ref name=\"Telopea\">{{cite journal |last1=Thompson |first1=Joy |title=A revision of the genus ''Leptospermum'' (Myrtaceae) |journal=Telopea |date=1989 |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=351\u2013352}}</ref><ref name=FloraBase>{{FloraBase|name=''Leptospermum maxwellii''|id=5851}}</ref>\n\n==Taxonomy and naming==\n''Leptospermum maxwellii'' was first formally described in 1920 by [[Spencer Le Marchant Moore]] and the description was published in the ''[[Botanical Journal of the Linnean Society|Journal of the Linnean Society, Botany]]'' from specimens collected by [[George Maxwell]] near the [[Fitzgerald River]].<ref name=APNI>{{cite web|title=''Leptospermum maxwellii''|url= https://id.biodiversity.org.au/instance/apni/525564|publisher=APNI|accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"S.Moore\">{{cite journal |last1=Moore |first1=Spencer Le M. |title=A Contribution to the Flora of Australia |journal=The Journal of the Linnean Society, Botany |date=1920 |volume=45 |page=201 |url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/8410#page/215/mode/1up |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref> The [[Botanical name|specific epithet]] (''maxwellii'') honours the collector of the [[Type (biology)|type]] specimens.<ref name=\"Sharr\">{{cite book |author=[[Francis Aubie Sharr]]|title=Western Australian Plant Names and their Meanings |date=2019 |publisher=Four Gables Press |location=Kardinya, Western Australia |isbn=9780958034180 |page=249}}</ref>\n\n==Distribution and habitat==\nThis tea tree grows on stony ridges in sandy soils over granite or laterite, in the [[Esperance Plains]] and [[Mallee (biogeographic region)|Mallee]] [[IBRA|biogeographic regions]].<ref name=\"Telopea\" /><ref name=\"FloraBase\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q15368843}}\n\n[[Category:Leptospermum|maxwellii]]\n[[Category:Flora of Western Australia]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1920]]\n", "name_user": "Allthingsnative", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leptospermum_maxwellii"}
{"title_page": "Josh Revak", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Josh Revak\n| birth_name          = Joshua Carl Revak\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1981|1|21}}\n| birth_place         = [[Two Harbors, Minnesota]], U.S.\n| branch              = {{Army|United States}}\n| battles             = [[Iraq War]]\n| serviceyears        = 2001\u20132008\n| office              = Member of the [[Alaska Senate]]<br>from the M district\n| termstart           = November 2, 2019\n| appointer           = [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]\n| predecessor         = [[Chris Birch (politician)|Chris Birch]]\n| office2             = Member of the<br>[[Alaska House of Representatives]]<br>from the 25th district\n| termstart2          = January 15, 2019\n| termend2            = November 2, 2019\n| predecessor2        = Chris Birch\n| successor2          = [[Mel Gillis]]\n| alma_mater          = [[Alaska Pacific University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Joshua Carl Revak''' (born January 21, 1981) is an American politician, serving since November 2, 2019 as a member of the [[Alaska Senate]].  Originally elected to the [[Alaska House of Representatives]] in 2018, Revak was appointed to the Senate to replace [[Chris Birch (politician)|Chris Birch]], whom he replaced in the House, when Birch died suddenly in August 2019.\n\n==Early life and military service==\nRevak was born and raised on a farm in [[Minnesota]]. He enlisted in the [[United States Army]] shortly after the [[September 11 attacks]]. After being severely wounded by a mortar attack in [[Iraq]], Revak and was honorably discharged in 2008 and returned to Minnesota.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.akleg.gov/basis/Member/Detail/31?code=REA|title=Alaska State Legislature|website=www.akleg.gov|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2009, Revak moved to [[Alaska]], where he worked in the office of Congressman [[Don Young]], serving as his Military and Veterans Affairs Liaison and Political Advisor. During this time, he earned a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Alaska Pacific University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alaskapacific.edu/stories/same-blood-different-mud-2/|title=Same Blood. Different Mud. \u2013 Alaska Pacific University|website=www.alaskapacific.edu|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2018, Revak was elected to serve in the [[Alaska House of Representatives]] to represent the 25th district. After the death of incumbent [[Chris Birch (politician)|Chris Birch]] in 2019, Revak was nominated by Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] to serve fill his vacant seat the [[Alaska Senate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Josh_Revak|title=Josh Revak|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2019/11/02/josh-revak-confirmed-to-senate-district-m/|title=Josh Revak Confirmed to Senate District M \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Revak, Josh}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Alaska Republicans]][[Category:Alaska Pacific University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Members of the Alaska House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Alaska state senators]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:People from Anchorage, Alaska]]\n[[Category:People from Lake County, Minnesota]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Josh Revak\n| birth_place         = [[Minnesota]], U.S.\n| branch              = {{army|United States}}\n| battles             = [[Iraq War]]\n| serviceyears        = 2001\u20132008\n| office              = Member of the [[Alaska Senate]]<br>from the M district\n| termstart           = November 2, 2019\n| nominator           = [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]]\n| predecessor         = [[Chris Birch (politician)|Chris Birch]]\n| office2             = Member of the<br>[[Alaska House of Representatives]]<br>from the 25th district\n| termstart2          = November 6, 2018\n| termend2            = November 2, 2019\n| successor2          = Mel Gillis\n| alma_mater          = [[Alaska Pacific University]] ([[Master of Business Administration|MBA]])\n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n}}\n\n'''Josh Revak''' is an American politician, currently serving as a member of the [[Alaska Senate]]. Revak has previously served as a member of the [[Alaska House of Representatives]] from November 6, 2018 to November 2, 2019.\n\n== Early life and military service ==\nRevak was born and raised on a farm in [[Minnesota]]. He enlisted in the [[United States Army]] shortly after the [[September 11 attacks]]. After being severely wounded by a mortar attack in [[Iraq]], Revak and was honorably discharged in 2008 and returned to Minnesota.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.akleg.gov/basis/Member/Detail/31?code=REA|title=Alaska State Legislature|website=www.akleg.gov|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 2009, Revak moved to [[Alaska]], where he worked in the office of Congressman [[Don Young]], serving as his Military and Veterans Affairs Liaison and Political Advisor. During this time, he earned a [[Master of Business Administration]] from [[Alaska Pacific University]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alaskapacific.edu/stories/same-blood-different-mud-2/|title=Same Blood. Different Mud. \u2013 Alaska Pacific University|website=www.alaskapacific.edu|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref> In 2018, Revak was elected to serve in the [[Alaska House of Representatives]] to represent the 25th district. After the death of incumbent [[Chris Birch (politician)|Chris Birch]] in 2019, Revak was nominated by Governor [[Mike Dunleavy (politician)|Mike Dunleavy]] to serve fill his vacant seat the [[Alaska Senate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ballotpedia.org/Josh_Revak|title=Josh Revak|website=Ballotpedia|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gov.alaska.gov/newsroom/2019/11/02/josh-revak-confirmed-to-senate-district-m/|title=Josh Revak Confirmed to Senate District M \u2013 Mike Dunleavy|website=gov.alaska.gov|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Revak, Josh}}\n[[Category:Alaska Republicans]][[Category:Alaska Pacific University alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Alaska House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:Alaska state senators]]\n[[Category:American army personnel of the Iraq War]]\n[[Category:People from Anchorage, Alaska]]\n[[Category:People from Lake County, Minnesota]]\n", "name_user": "RadioKAOS", "label": "safe", "comment": "Guess it needed more cleanup than that", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_Revak"}
